<?xml version="1.0"?><collection name="D0841-B"><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>The Swedish Church Assembly, the decision-making body for the Church of Sweden, voted 160-81 to approve a blessing ceremony for same-sex partnerships.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="48"><scu uid="78" label="Sweden's church allows gay partnership blessing ceremonies" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The partnership is based on existing marriage laws but is distinct from them.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="32,42,5"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Gay couples can get married as soon as the law is published in the official government registry, which could happen as early as Friday or within two weeks at the latest, parliament's press office said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>&quot;But I talked to several of the senators, and we'll see,&quot; he added.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The Roman Catholic Church, which held much sway over the government just a generation ago when Gen. Francisco Franco was in power, adamantly opposed gay marriage.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The debate in Canada began in December, when the Supreme Court ruled that passage of same-sex legislation would not violate the constitution.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="48"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Outside the stately 19th-century chamber, activists waved the rainbow flags symbolizing the international gay rights movement.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Randall Ellis, executive director of the Lesbian/Gay Rights Lobby of Texas, said there are more than 43,000 same sex couples in Texas, third behind New York and California.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- FRANCE: In October 1999 the Civil Pact of Solidarity (PACS) giving legal status to non-married couples, including gays, came into effect.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>Sweden's Lutheran Church on Thursday decided to let homosexual partners be blessed in special church ceremonies but not in traditional weddings.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="55"><scu uid="78" label="Sweden's church allows gay partnership blessing ceremonies" weight="1"/><scu uid="82" label="Gay marriage remains illegal in some countries" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- BRITAIN: A bill passed by parliament in March 2004 and expected to come into force in December this year, opens up the possibility for gays to sign a &quot;civil partnership&quot; which would authorise the continued payment of a pension in the event of the death of a partner or exempt the survivor from inheritance tax on property owned by the deceased partner.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>Some 18 states, meanwhile, have formally declared that marriage is exclusively for heterosexual couples.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;We are a nation of minorities,&quot; Martin said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The 350-seat Congress of Deputies approved the measure Thursday by a vote of 187-147 with four abstentions.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- NEW ZEALAND: The New Zealand parliament adopted in December 2004 legislation which confers to gay couples, who have officially declared their union, to have the same rights as heterosexual married couples.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>&quot;It is neither justified nor fair to deprive people of certain rights because of their sexual orientation,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Pittman asked Rosenberg if Connecticut's law preventing same-sex couples from marrying is any different from a Virginia law that prevented interracial couples from marrying until it was declared unconstitutional.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>As approved by the House, the measure would define marriage as a union between one man and one woman and would prohibit the state or any local government from creating or recognizing &quot;any legal status identical or similar to marriage,&quot; such as civil unions.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>In debate before the vote, Prime Minister Jose Luis Rodriguez Zapatero said the dry language of the Spanish reform masks &quot;an immense change in the lives of thousands of citizens.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>A right is a right and that is what this vote tonight is all about.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Partners will even be able to dissolve the agreement in a form of divorce.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Single people may adopt but not avowed homosexual couples.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Society now legally recognizes gay relationships for the first time.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The judge did not immediately rule.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>But it is important for this to be called marriage so people know that it is the same thing for everyone,&quot; he added.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Last week, the measure passed the House 53-17 vote.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The Senate, where conservatives hold the largest number of seats, rejected it last week, but that chamber is only an advisory one and final say on legislation rests with the Congress of Deputies.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Homosexual rights activists urged the government Friday to grant homosexual couples the right to marry.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="0,14"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>If approved, it would mean that in Idaho, &quot;a marriage between a man and a woman is the only domestic legal union that shall be valid or recognized.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- SWITZERLAND: On June 5 referendum the Swiss voted in favour of a &quot;registered partnership&quot; for same-sex couples.</line><line>- SOUTH AFRICA: In September 2002 the South African constitutional court recognised the right of gay couples to adopt children.</line><line>Homosexual couples have the same rights as heterosexual partners, except in the areas of insemination and adoption.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Dewhurst didn't identify the 11 senators or release copies of their letter.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>While a slew of Israeli men were married in Toronto City Hall earlier this year, for example, the Israeli Interior Ministry does not recognize those unions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Canada's House of Commons passed legislation that would legalize gay marriage by the end of July as long as the Senate also passes the bill, which it is expected to do.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="10,19,37,6"><scu uid="74" label="Canada legalized gay marriage" weight="4"/></annotation></line><line>Oscar-winning Spanish film director Pedro Almodovar, who is gay, said 21st-century families are different and don't have to reflect the traditional Catholic model.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>GLAD used a similar argument in Massachusetts, where gay marriage became legal after a 2003 state Supreme Judicial Court ruling, and similar lawsuits are pending in other states.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The legislation, however, states that the bill only covers civil unions, not religious ones, and no clergy would be forced to perform same-sex ceremonies unless they choose to do so.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- PORTUGAL: A 2001 law recognises de facto couples, regardless of sex, of more than two years and provides a number of tax benefits enjoyed by married couples.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Kelly Schackelford of Dallas, president of the conservative Free Market Foundation, said it was necessary to lock the ban into the constitution to keep from having judicial challenges to the Texas marriage law as is occurring in other states.</line><line>Eleven senators, if all hold firm, could kill the measure.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Most of those amendments were adopted after Massachusetts' highest court legalized same-sex marriage in 2003, raising fears that courts in other states might do the same.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>&quot;That's a perversion of our democracy and how our system is supposed to work.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>He said his party is considering challenging the law before the Constitutional Court, Spain's highest tribunal.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Meg Munn, minister for equality, said the government expected 4,500 couples to get &quot;partnered&quot; in the first year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>There are an estimated 34,000 gay and lesbian couples in Canada, according to government statistics.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Sen. Juan Hinojosa, D-McAllen, said he also was among the 11 opponents.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>A lawyer for eight gay couples argued in court Tuesday that Connecticut's marriage laws illegally create a separate class of people based on sexual orientation.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="8" sums="12,25,29,42,44,48,49,55"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>In Denmark gay couples can only adopt their own children from previous relationships.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>There are currently 18 U.S. states with constitutional amendments against gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="25,43,57,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>On the Net:</line><line>Munter noted that is has been 30 years since the first homosexual couple applied for a marriage license in Canada.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Several members of the conservative opposition Popular Party, which vehemently opposed the bill, shouted: &quot;This is a disgrace.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>In the United States, gay marriage is opposed by a majority of Americans, according to an Associated Press-Ipsos poll taken in November, shortly after constitutional amendments in 11 states to ban same-sex marriage were approved.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="3,35"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>&quot;Matrimony shall have the same requirements and effects regardless of whether the persons involved are of the same or different sex,&quot; the bill states.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;We know that it has been somewhat contentious in Canada, but at the same time the Canadians have largely approached this issue in a rational and democratic way and are providing a very positive model for the rest of the world,&quot; Sklar said.</line><line>&quot;Lesbians and gay people are your brothers and sisters, neighbors, friends and co-workers.</line><line>Charles McVety, a spokesman for Defend Marriage Canada and president of Canada Christian College, called the vote an &quot;onerous breach of trust and the deconstruction of so much that is dear to our hearts.&quot;</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>The Senate's operating procedure also requires a two-thirds parliamentary vote to debate any legislation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>&quot;I'm pretty hopeful and optimistic,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>&quot;Judges all over the country are doing an end run around the people,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Vermont and Connecticut allow civil unions for gays, while California, New Jersey, Maine and Hawaii recognize more limited forms of gay partnership.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="84" label="Some states have legalized gay unions/partnerships" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>Later this year a government-appointed committee is expected to file a report on whether the law allowing civil unions between homosexuals should be changed to include marriage as well.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>A country-by-country review of current legislation:</line><line>In November 2002 a law was passed allowing gay couples to adopt.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="6" sums="10,13,37,40,43,6"/></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>But homosexual couples cannot choose to marry, and consequently they lose their entitlement to many civil rights, &quot; she said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Zapatero lacks a majority in the chamber but got more than enough help from small regional-based parties that tend to be his allies.</line><line>Parliament has legalized gay marriage, angering conservatives and clergy as it made heavily Roman Catholic Spain the world's third country to grant full recognition to same-sex couples, even letting them adopt children.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="10,21,23"><scu uid="75" label="Spain legalized gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>In Idaho, a proposed constitutional amendment banning gay marriage passed 26-9 in the state Senate on Wednesday and will go to voters this November.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="14,36"><scu uid="88" label="Some states were voting on gay unions" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>&quot;It accords people in same-sex relationships the same sort of rights and responsibilities that are available to married couples, &quot; she said.</line><line>The partnerships will allow homosexuals to benefit from a dead partner's pension, grant next-of-kin rights in hospitals and exempt them from inheritance tax on a partner's home.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Constitutional amendments must be approved by two-thirds of the 31-member Senate, or 21 senators.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The Family Institute of Connecticut, which opposes gay marriage, has asked to intervene in the case, claiming the state attorney general's office is not vigorously defending Connecticut's marriage laws.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="42,5"/></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>But at present, the problem is that they cannot choose,&quot; Wang said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>&quot;To allow same-sex couples to marry would not be removing a barrier to marriage, but redefining marriage itself,&quot; state Attorney General Patrick DeAlmeida told the seven-member court.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="21"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Sweden is the only one to authorise adoption by gay couples (since February 2003).</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Rajoy said that if the vast majority of countries don't accept gay marriage, including some run by Socialists, there must be a reason.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;This is the beginning of the formal fight against the redefinition of marriage,&quot; McVety said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Dewhurst, nevertheless, said Thursday that he hoped the measure will win Senate approval before the session adjourns 10 days from now.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The amendment would have defined marriage as a union of one woman and one man.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>The court is not expected to issue a decision for months.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Although gay marriage is already legal in seven provinces, the bill now grants all same-sex couples in Canada the same legal rights as those in traditional union between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="13"/></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Because Taiwan does not allow homosexual marriages or civil unions, there is no way for Jennifer's girlfriend to come to Taiwan as her partner.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The registered partnership allows an individual gay or lesbian to adopt a child while living in a gay couple.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Overall, the city has taken 510 bookings for the coming months, thought to be the highest in the country.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Taiwan Tongzhi Hotline Association Public Affairs Director Ashley Wu said that homosexual couples are facing great difficulties in life and death because Taiwan does not allow homosexual marriages or civil unions.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="87" label="Rights for gay couples are being advocated in Taiwan" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>DeAlmeida fielded the brunt of the New Jersey judges' questions, including what might be protected by preventing same-sex marriage in New Jersey, one of 16 states where it's specifically illegal to discriminate based on sexual orientation.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Hundreds of couples are expected to go ahead quickly, with Brighton in southern England conducting 198 ceremonies before the end of the year.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>But surveys also show Spaniards about evenly split over whether gay couples should be allowed to adopt children.</line><line>We have been fighting for many years,&quot; said Beatriz Gimeno, a longtime leader of the gay rights movement in Spain.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Two U.S. states took up the issue of gay marriage on Wednesday, with preliminary arguments heard in a New Jersey Supreme Court case and a constitutional amendment against gay marriage passing in Idaho's state Senate.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="7" sums="11,12,23,29,36,42,5"><scu uid="80" label="Some states are debating gay unions " weight="3"/><scu uid="83" label="Idaho banned gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>The two associations made the revelations during a Legislative Yuan hearing Friday on the legalization of homosexual marriages.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Still, polls suggest Spaniards support gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="4" sums="32,36,49,6"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>In the United States, the federal government does not recognize same-sex marriage and most states refuse to acknowledge marriage certificates from gay and lesbian couples, regardless of where they wed.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>He called the proposal &quot;a misguided solution for a problem that doesn't even exist.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The couples, with the help of the Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders, sued in 2004 in an attempt to overturn the state's ban on gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="29"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>But it does not confer the tax advantages enjoyed by married couples or the right to adopt.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>We are not legislating, ladies and gentlemen, for remote, unknown people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>The issue has been debated since the secularized Scandinavian country recognized civil unions for homosexual couples in 1994.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Connecticut Assistant Attorney General Jane Rosenberg defended the laws Tuesday, arguing that there is no fundamental right to marry.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="80" label="Some states are debating gay unions " weight="3"/></annotation></line><line>She said it was reasonable for the state to create civil unions to give gay couples the legal rights of marriage while also dealing with administrative issues, such as federal Medicaid and Medicare programs, which do not recognize gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="21,22"/></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>&quot;Jennifer&quot; (alias) met her Chinese girlfriend in England when she was studying for her doctoral degree.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The bill passed as expected, despite opposition from Conservatives and religious leaders.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Before the federal legislation the majority of provinces had approved gay marriages.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Sen. Rodney Ellis, D-Houston, who earlier this week used a parliamentary &quot;tag&quot; to delay the committee hearing on the controversial proposal, said he was one of the signers.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The Spanish Bishops Conference lashed out at the law, saying that with it and a bill passed Wednesday making it easier for Spaniards to divorce, &quot;marriage, understood as the union of a man and a woman, is no longer provided for in our laws.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Under the Civil Partnership Act, which won Royal Assent in November 2004, gay and lesbian couples who want to form a partnership must register their intentions with local councils.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The state of New Jersey in December 1997 allowed adoption by homosexual couples.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Zapatero has also pushed through legislation allowing stem-cell research and wants to loosen Spain's restrictive abortion law.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>The legality of same-sex marriage is also being debated in courts in California, New Jersey, New York and Washington state.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="12,51"><scu uid="80" label="Some states are debating gay unions " weight="3"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Dewhurst said the proposal would strengthen the state's existing law against homosexual marriages.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="57"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Gay couples have the same rights as heterosexual couples, in particular insofar as inheritance and succession rights are concerned, but do not have the right to adopt.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Elsewhere Tuesday, New Hampshire lawmakers voted overwhelmingly to defeat a proposed constitutional amendment to ban gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="32"><scu uid="86" label="New Hampshire rejected a ban on gay marriage" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>It bans adoption and medically-assisted reproduction.</line><line>Noel Mamere, the Green party mayor of the Bordeaux suburb of Begles in southwest France, &quot;married&quot; two gay men in June but a court declared the ceremony void the following month.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>At the end of the day, no argument in favor of exclusion can withstand what people see with their own eyes: That it is wrong to treat people that they care about in a way that diminishes their personal choice.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The bill is expected to be passed by the Senate at the end of July.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>&quot;This is an important piece of legislation that gives legal recognition to relationships which until now were invisible in the eyes of the law,&quot; Munn was quoted by a local media.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- CROATIA: The parliament adopted a law in mid-July 2003, a law which provides gay couples with the same rights as defacto heterosexual couples.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;Same-sex marriage rights are extremely variable in the United States and whether Canadian marriages will be respected, state by state, is something yet to be determined,&quot; Sklar said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Committee approval would clear the way for a showdown on the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>In its first display of anti-government activism in 20 years, it endorsed a June 18 rally in which hundreds of thousands of people marched through Madrid in opposition to the bill.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Gay couples are not doing any better either, according to the Taiwan Tongzhi [Homosexual] Hotline Association, which revealed that &quot;Ted&quot; (alias) , a gay man whose boyfriend underwent surgery for cancer, was not allowed to take care of his boyfriend in the hospital because the hospital did not consider him as a family member.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>&quot;It is necessary to oppose these unfair laws through all legitimate means,&quot; a conference statement said, alluding to its hint last month that town hall officials who oppose gay marriage should refuse to preside over such ceremonies.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Jennifer is just one of the cases revealed by the Taiwan Leshand Association on lesbian couples' real life predicaments.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Rosenberg responded that race is not an essential part of marriage but gender is.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>According to most polls, a majority of Canadians supports the right for gays and lesbians to marry.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="3" sums="13,37,6"/></line><line>Massachusetts is the only state that allows gay marriages, although Vermont and Connecticut have approved same-sex civil unions.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="22"><scu uid="84" label="Some states have legalized gay unions/partnerships" weight="2"/><scu uid="81" label="Massachusetts legalized gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Gender/Sexuality Rights Association Secretary-General Wang Ping said that homosexuals should enjoy civil rights just like any other people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;This has been a long, arduous road,&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>&quot;Our view is that civil partnerships are transformative for the lives of individual couples and their rights, but also for society more generally.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>I am not going to get married.</line><line>The gay marriage bill was the boldest and most divisive initiative of the liberal social agenda Zapatero has embarked on since taking office in April 2004.</line><line>The former allows gays to adopt children, but Belgium so far is just considering it.</line><line>&quot;It is a historic day for the world's homosexuals.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>&quot;It is never right to allow the majority to decide the rights of minorities,&quot; he said referring to the November election that would be required to amend the constitution if the Legislature approves the bill.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>In his view, Dec. 21, the date when the first partnerships take place, will be even bigger because that will see gay and lesbian people removing discrimination by holding their own ceremonies.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- NORTHERN EUROPE: Denmark was the first country in the world to authorise (on October 1, 1989) a &quot;registered partnership&quot; between gays.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>&quot;I think the prime minister has committed a grave act of irresponsibility,&quot; Rajoy said.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Associated Press Writer Chris Newmarker in Trenton contributed to this report.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Furthermore, 52 percent of the surveyed said that they want to be entitled to the rights enjoyed by married people, including lower taxes and the right to sign their partners' surgery consent forms.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Other cities which have seen strong interest include London, Manchester, Birmingham, Newcastle and Edinburgh.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>&quot;I believe that we probably will have the votes.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>David Buckell, attorney for the seven couples, talked about the personal stories of some of his clients.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The Netherlands and Belgium are the only other two countries that recognize gay marriage nationwide.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>I believe the courts will correct this injustice of not allowing us to marry.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The legislation drafted by Prime Minister Paul Martin's minority Liberal Party government was also expected to easily pass the Senate and become federal law by the end of July.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>&quot;I don't like marriage.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line><line>Conservative opposition lawmakers said they might challenge the law in court, while the church issued a veiled call for civil authorities who oppose gay marriage to refuse to wed same-sex couples.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="5" sums="14,25,3,35,44"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Currently, 17 U.S. states have constitutional amendments banning same-sex marriage, and seven will vote in Novemeber on such amendments.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="2" sums="37,43"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Though hundreds of foreigners have come to Canada to seek civil ceremonies since gay marriages were first allowed in Ontario and British Columbia in 2003, not all countries or states recognize the unions.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Hundreds of homosexual couples in Britain are preparing to form civil partnerships in the coming weeks as the Civil Partnership Act comes into force on Monday.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="29,5,55"><scu uid="79" label="Some countries have legalized gay civil unions/partnerships" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Conservative groups filed documents contending that allowing same-sex marriage would harm society.</line><line>Opponents argued that a constitutional amendment isn't necessary because Idaho state law already defines marriage as being between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="51"><scu uid="83" label="Idaho banned gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The poll had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Campaigners says the law ends inequalities for same-sex couples.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The Netherlands and Belgium are the only other nations that allow gay marriage nationwide.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="18"/></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>Baltimore Judge Brooke Murdock ruled that prohibiting gay marriage was discriminatory and in violation of the state's constitution<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="57"><scu uid="77" label="Maryland rejected a ban on gay unions " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>But he also declined to identify the others or say whether they included both Democrats and Republicans.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Churches have expressed concern that their clergy would be compelled by law to perform same-sex ceremonies, with couples taking them to court or human rights tribunals if refused.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>We are expanding opportunities for the happiness of our neighbors, our work colleagues, our friends, our relatives.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Norway (1993), Sweden (1994), Iceland (1996) and Finland (2001) followed suit.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>A 1973 Maryland law rules that only marriages between a man and a woman are valid, but Murdock ruled in favor of 19 gays and lesbians who filed suit last year, insisting that the law violated the state constitution.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="20,43,44"><scu uid="77" label="Maryland rejected a ban on gay unions " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Thirty-three of Martin's Liberal lawmakers voted against the bill and a Cabinet minister resigned Tuesday over the contentious legislation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The vote halted this year's campaign for a constitutional ban of same-sex unions in the state.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>&quot;And in a nation of minorities, it is important that you don't cherry pick rights.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Alan Wardle of gay campaign group Stonewall, said the importance of the change should not be underestimated.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>Following Murdock's ruling, Maryland's Republican Governor Robert Ehrlich spoke out in favor of a constitutional amendment stipulating that marriages must be between a man and a woman.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>The Roman Catholic Church, the predominant Christian denomination in Canada, has vigorously opposed the legislation, as well as major Islamic and Sikh organizations whose members believe the law would rock the foundations of traditional family.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The two parties enjoy some but not all of the tax and social benefits of married couples, in particular in the field of inheritance.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Martin, a Roman Catholic, hailed Tuesday's 158-133 vote as a necessary step for human rights and the protection of minorities.</line><line>&quot;We will, in the next election, be able to correct this incredible democratic deficit before us today.&quot;</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>Wu pointed out that his organization conducted a poll at the end of 2005 on homosexual marriages, and the poll showed that 89 percent of the homosexuals surveyed agree that homosexual marriages should be legalized, and 81 percent consider it to be a legal right.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Flanked by clergymen, McVety vowed his group would work topple MPs who supported the legislation in the next general elections.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>&quot;Connecticut has done so much to allow us to be a family.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>The Spanish government Thursday approved plans for homosexual marriage, including the right of gay couples to adopt, making the country the most liberal in Europe, with Belgium and the Netherlands, in the field of gay rights.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="4" sums="11,30,41,49"><scu uid="75" label="Spain legalized gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Gay marriage is prohibited in all but one of the 50 U.S. states.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The bill became law immediately.</line><line>Under the divorce law reform, couples can end their marriage without a mandatory separation period or having to state a reason, as required under the old legislation.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>&quot;The only answer is that the state does not think their relationships are worthy.&quot;</line><line>The state also has no legal barriers for same-sex couples to adopt children and recognizes domestic partnerships, although those do not offer all the legal protections of marriage.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>Adoption by homosexual couples remains illegal.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>After the final tally was announced, activists watching from the spectator section of the ornate chamber cried and cheered, waving to lawmakers and blowing them kisses.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>The first ceremonies under the Civil Partnerships Act can take place in Northern Ireland on Dec. 19, followed by Scotland the next day and England and Wales on Dec. 21.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>However the individual alone is legally responsible for the child and not the couple.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>Sweden has a liberal attitude toward homosexuals, but gay marriage is not yet legal.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="22,32,57"><scu uid="82" label="Gay marriage remains illegal in some countries" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>But the law does not change the marriage act which defines it as a union between a &quot;man and woman.&quot;</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Some 20 bishops took part.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>That law &quot;is nothing less than the government's announcement that these are second-class citizens,&quot; Ben Klein, a senior attorney for Gay and Lesbian Advocates and Defenders, told Superior Court Judge Patty Jenkins Pittman.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>The state of New Jersey did not make that argument in defending its ban, but said allowing same-sex marriage is an issue for lawmakers, not judges.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>State officials immediately appealed the ruling, setting the stage for another court battle on the controversial issue.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Roberta Sklar, communications director for the National Gay and Lesbian Task Force in Washington, D.C., said same-sex American couples applaud Canadians.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Gay activists wept with joy and thanked lawmakers by blowing them kisses.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>The Senate State Affairs Committee, meanwhile, began a late-night hearing on the measure.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Alex Munter, national spokesman for Canadians for Equal Marriage, which has led the debate in favor of the law, was triumphant after the vote: &quot;The genius of Canada, almost unparalleled in the world, is built on shared identity, out of respect for each other.&quot;</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>It is the first day they can apply for a civil partnership to cement their relationships in law by notifying Registry Offices of their intent, although the couples will have to wait 15 days before holding a ceremony.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>When Jennifer graduated this year, she faced the difficult choice of staying in England with her girlfriend or returning to Taiwan to take care of her ailing mother.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Supporters say the amendment would prevent judges from overturning that law.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>Last year, Connecticut approved civil unions for gay couples, which gives them the same legal rights as heterosexual married couples, but that law also defined marriage as existing only between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="16,37,6"><scu uid="84" label="Some states have legalized gay unions/partnerships" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20051027.0511"><line>More than 7 million of Sweden's 9 million inhabitants belong to the Church of Sweden, but few attend church regularly.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>Unlike marriages, the signing of the legal partnership papers does not need to happen in public.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>But enough allies rallied to support the bill that has been debated for months.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="32"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>A survey released in May by pollster Instituto Opina said 62 percent of Spaniards support the government's action on gay marriage, and 30 percent oppose it.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>&quot;How do plaintiffs answer their children's questions about why they are not married?&quot; he said.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Dewhurst said he received a letter from 11 senators, asking that the same-sex marriage ban not be brought to the Senate floor.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>In January, a Baltimore judge ruled that a law against gay marriage violates the Maryland Constitution's guarantee of equal rights.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="2" sums="19,36"><scu uid="77" label="Maryland rejected a ban on gay unions " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>Massachusetts is the only US state to recognize gay marriage, while Vermont and Connecticut recognize civil unions for same-sex couples.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="5" sums="13,19,20,22,43"><scu uid="84" label="Some states have legalized gay unions/partnerships" weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- GERMANY: On August 1, 2001 a &quot;registered partnership&quot; came into effect which gives gay couples some rights enjoyed by different-sex married couples, such as; the possibility of adopting the name of the partner, inheritance rights, gifts and tax on possessions, health and unemployment insurance.</line></document><document name="XIN_ENG_20051205.0127"><line>The Act does not use the term &quot;gay marriage&quot; but the civil partnerships have clearly been designed to be as close to a marriage contract as possible, the Sky news reported.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>Canada's House of Commons passed landmark legislation Tuesday to legalize gay marriage, granting same-sex couples legal rights equal to those in traditional unions between a man and a woman.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="7" sums="11,14,23,25,41,43,49"><scu uid="74" label="Canada legalized gay marriage" weight="4"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>In all these countries the law gives gay couples the same legal and social rights as married heterosexual couples.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>&quot;Now comes the hardest part, which is changing society's mentality.&quot;</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- CANADA: The Canadian lower house of parliament approved on June 28 a bill legalising gay marriages and adoption.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>The bill, a divisive plank in the ruling Socialists' platform for social reform, gives homosexual couples the same rights as heterosexual ones.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>&quot;Marriage, as a social mechanism, offers many rights and protections.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- UNITED STATES: Since 2004 Massachusetts became the only US state to authorise gay marriages while Vermont and Connecticut, also in the northeast of the country, allow civil unions which offer homosexuals some of the rights enjoyed by heterosexual couples.<annotation scu-count="2" sum-count="1" sums="40"><scu uid="84" label="Some states have legalized gay unions/partnerships" weight="2"/><scu uid="81" label="Massachusetts legalized gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line><line>- BELGIUM: Marriage between homosexuals became legal on June 1, 2003: since February 2004 it also covers foreigners.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>More than 200 witnesses testified against the ban in a committee hearing in the House last month.</line></document><document name="CNA_ENG_20060324.0018"><line>&quot;If homosexuals are citizens equal to others, they should be allowed to choose to enter into marriage or not.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>In the United States, Massachusetts is the only state to recognize gay marriage.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="1" sums="43"><scu uid="81" label="Massachusetts legalized gay marriage" weight="1"/></annotation></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Both supporters and opponents of gay marriage held rallies Wednesday outside the building housing the high court.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050629.0102"><line>It was the last major piece of legislation before Parliament recessed for summer and comes on the first anniversary of Martin's leadership.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>- NETHERLANDS: The Dutch Senate adopted in December 2000 legislation authorising civil homosexual marriage, the first country to do so, and the adoption by two same-sex parents of children provided the children have Dutch nationality.<annotation scu-count="0" sum-count="1" sums="40"/></line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20050701.0030"><line>Popular Party leader Mariano Rajoy said Zapatero has deeply divided Spain and should have sought a consensus in parliament that recognized same-sex unions but didn't call them marriages.</line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20060121.0324"><line>The issue of same-sex marriage is open for debate in Maryland, after a judge in the eastern US state rejected a state law banning such unions.<annotation scu-count="1" sum-count="3" sums="12,41,51"><scu uid="77" label="Maryland rejected a ban on gay unions " weight="2"/></annotation></line></document><document name="AFP_ENG_20050630.0469"><line>For the union to be valid one of the partners needs to be Belgian or to live in Belgium.</line><line>In the cantons of Geneva and Zurich forms of the French PACS operate for all administrative questions.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The state Supreme Court has not yet ruled on whether that group may become part of the case.</line><line>Jeffrey Busch of Wilton attended Tuesday's hearing with partner Stephen Davis and son Elijah.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060215.1360"><line>Supreme Court Justices in New Jersey grilled lawyers about why the state should prevent homosexual couples from marrying in a case involving seven same-sex couples who sued the state, saying it is violating its constitution by denying them the right to marry.</line></document><document name="NYT_ENG_20050519.0253"><line>Opponents argue that it is a discriminatory attack on one group of people.</line></document><document name="APW_ENG_20060322.0092"><line>The vote was 207-125.</line></document></collection>